# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brandon-crawford
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brandon-crawford/2008-major-league-baseball-draft] The **2008 Major League Baseball draft**, was an annual choosing of high school and college baseball players, held on June 5 and 6, 2008.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The **2011 Major League Baseball season** began on Thursday, March 31, and ended on Wednesday, September 28.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p01] This marked the first time a season began on a Thursday since 1976, and the first time a regular season ended on a Wednesday since 1990.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The 82nd edition of the Major League Baseball All-Star Game was played at Chase Field in Phoenix, Arizona, on July 12 with the National League defeating the American League for the second straight year, by a score of 5–1.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p01] As had been the case since 2003, the league winning that game had home field advantage in the World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Accordingly, the World Series began on October 19, and ended on October 28, with the St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Louis Cardinals winning in seven games over the Texas Rangers.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The season is notable for its wild card chase on the last day of the regular season.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Four teams announced new managers for the 2011 season after the former manager retired from baseball.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Two more teams joined the growing cable-exclusive telecast teams in 2011.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox Sports Midwest produced and televised all St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Louis Cardinals games on the cable station, along with selected areas of the Cardinals' DMA outside St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Louis including Fox Sports Tennessee in Tennessee, Fox Sports Indiana in parts of Indiana, and SportsSouth in Arkansas and parts of Oklahoma.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The 2010 season was their last season of splitting games with KSDK.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Minnesota Twins also joined the group, with Fox Sports North becoming their exclusive local home.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The 2010 season was their last season of splitting games with WFTC.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Atlanta Braves games that aired on WPCH-TV were produced by and simulcast on Fox Sports South or SportSouth, marking the first season since 1972 which local Braves telecasts weren't produced by Turner Sports.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TSN2 held rights to the ESPN Sunday Night Baseball telecasts.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In Australia, it was free to air channel One HD and showed up to five games live per week, and European channel ESPN America broadcast games as well.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] For international viewers, MLB International broadcast the All-Star Game, the NLCS and the World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN Radio served as MLB's national radio network, broadcasting *Sunday Night Baseball* as well as selected Saturday and holiday games during the regular season, the Home Run Derby and All-Star Game, and all postseason series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN Deportes Radio held the Spanish language rights to the Fall Classic.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim celebrated their 50th Anniversary in 2011.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] That year, the team name was altered to the California Angels.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] After being purchased by The Walt Disney Company in 1997, the team name was changed to the Anaheim Angels and after Arte Moreno purchased the team, the name was changed to its current moniker to the **Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim** in 2005.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] For the season, in addition to the patch, the Angels changed the color of the halo from silver to gold on their uniforms, just as it looked from 1971 through 1996.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In addition, on selected Friday night games, the team donned replicas of five of the six styles of uniforms they have worn, the most notable omission being that of the "Periwinkle Blue" era from 1997 to 2001, when Disney owned the team.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This was the Florida Marlins' final season at Sun Life Stadium, after 19 years, they moved to their new ballpark in downtown Miami, where they became the Miami Marlins.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Due to the U2 360° Tour concert scheduled June 29 at Sun Life Stadium and the needed time to set up the stage, the Marlins were forced to move their scheduled home games for June 24–26 against the Seattle Mariners to the Mariners' park at Safeco Field.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] As the Marlins were the home team, NL rules (no designated hitter) were applied.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Mariners and Marlins did not meet again in Miami until 2014.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Houston Astros were sold by Drayton McLane for US $680 million to a group led by Jim Crane, the founder of a transit logistics company.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Detroit Tigers retired Sparky Anderson's No.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Bert Blyleven, elected to the Class of 2011 of the Baseball Hall of Fame, was honored with the retirement of his uniform No.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Roberto Alomar, also a 2011 Hall of Fame class member, became the first member of the Toronto Blue Jays to have his number (#12) retired on July 31.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Atlanta Braves retired Bobby Cox's No.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] 6 prior to their game against the Chicago Cubs on August 12.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Trevor Hoffman, who had been the all-time saves leader until Mariano Rivera surpassed him on September 19, had his No.
[src:brandon-crawford/2011-major-league-baseball-season-p02] 51 retired by the San Diego Padres on August 21.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The **2012 Major League Baseball season** began on April 5, 2012 because during the MLB Spring Training it was the first of a two-game series between the Seattle Mariners and the Oakland Athletics at the Tokyo Dome in Japan.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] On November 22, 2011, a new contract between Major League Baseball and its players union was ratified, and as a result, an expanded playoff format adding two clubs would be adopted no later than 2013 according to the new Collective Bargaining Agreement.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The new format of the 2012 postseason used the 1 game series of the Wild Card round of the format for the 2012 postseason only.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The restriction against divisional rivals playing against each other in the Division Series round that had existed in previous years was eliminated, as the Baltimore Orioles and New York Yankees squared off in one of the best-of-five LDS in the American League.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] On April 4, 2012, it was the last day of the MLB Spring Training and ended with the new Marlins Park, as the newly renamed Miami Marlins hosted the defending World Series champion St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The regular season ended on Wednesday, October 3, 2012.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The entire master schedule was released on September 14, 2011.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Major League Baseball postseason was expanded to include a second wild card team in each league beginning in the 2012 season.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The season marked the last for the Houston Astros as a member of the National League.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Following the sale to new owner Jim Crane, the Astros agreed to move to the American League effective in the 2013 season, and would be assigned to the American League West, joining their in-state rivals, the Texas Rangers.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Major League Baseball All-Star Game's 83rd edition was held on July 10, 2012 at Kauffman Stadium in Kansas City, Missouri, with the National League winning the All-Star Game for the third consecutive year in an 8–0 shutout of the American League.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] With the win, the National League champion earned home field advantage for the World Series, which began on October 24, 2012 and ended on October 28, 2012 when the San Francisco Giants swept the Detroit Tigers.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Civil Rights Game was held on August 18, 2012 at Turner Field, as the Los Angeles Dodgers beat the host Atlanta Braves, 6–2.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The following managers were hired for the 2012 season after the former manager retired from baseball.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p01] At the end of the 2011 season, the following teams made replacements to their managers.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Five teams have made wholesale changes to their uniforms in 2012, while a sixth has new road uniforms.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Two other teams added alternate uniforms to their existing set.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The San Diego Padres were the first team to announce changes to their logos and uniform set on November 9.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The new primary features the "SD" cap logo inside a navy circle with the words "San Diego Padres Baseball Club" encircling it.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The "swinging friar" logo was also revived, albeit in the current colors.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Another secondary logo features the Padres script from last season below the depiction of Petco Park in sand and above the year of establishment; a blue and white version is used on the away and alternate uniforms.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The front of the home uniform remains the same, except that the sand trim in "Padres" is now in trim instead of a drop shadow and the addition of navy piping.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Originally they'll use the sand Petco patch on the left sleeve, but upon unveiling the uniforms, the "swinging friar" patch was placed instead.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The road uniforms now feature "San Diego" in an arched position with navy piping.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The alternate blue uniforms feature the "SD" cap logo on the left chest with white piping.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] All three uniforms now feature the block numerals on the reverse side.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The digital camouflage uniforms were retained, save for the change to block numerals.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The caps with the sand "SD" were retired.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Marlins unveiled their changes on November 11, 2011, as the team was rebranded as the Miami Marlins, complete with a new logo featuring a stylized Marlin jumping over an art deco colored "M" in coral, yellow and blue.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] "MIAMI" will grace the primary white uniform, and there will be an orange home alternate which feature the team name, while the black alt had been reduced to road alternate jersey.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The black cap is used for the regular home, away and black alternates, while the orange cap is paired with the orange alternates.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Marlins become the second team to use the city (or state) name on the home uniforms, after the Texas Rangers.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] November 15 saw the Baltimore Orioles redesign their road and home uniform sets and returned to a version of the cartoon logo used from the mid-1960s to 1988.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The home caps are white in front and black on the back with an orange bill, while the away caps will be all black with an orange bill, both featuring the cartoon bird.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] They also unveiled a modernized version of the orange alternate uniforms last worn in 1992, and were worn on select home games, but retained the black alternate uniforms paired with the black and orange cap with the "O's" script.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] As part of their golden anniversary season, the New York Mets modified their home and road uniforms to resemble the style worn in 1962, having their unveiling November 16.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In addition, the black alternate jersey (which will be worn occasionally on the road in 2012) is being phased out, to be replaced by a blue alternate starting in 2013.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The solid black cap with the blue/white/orange crest will also be retained for one more season, to be worn only with the black alternate jersey.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The black cap with blue bill and blue/orange crest has been eliminated.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In addition, the Mets have removed the color black from their batting-practice jerseys and caps; both will be blue with orange lettering/logos outlined in white.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Toronto Blue Jays unveiled new uniforms on November 18, returning to a variation of their vintage logo used from 1977 through 1996.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The new logo is similar to the original used from 1977–96, with a few exceptions: a more prominent maple leaf, a sleeker-looking blue jay, serifed modern lettering on the team name, and a split-line blue circle enclosing the logo.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The new uniforms are similarly based on the set used from 1989–96; a white home uniform with "Blue Jays", a grey road uniform with "Toronto", and a blue alternate uniform with "Blue Jays".
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The team/city name is arched above the secondary logo of the blue jay with the maple leaf, sans the baseball, situated on the left side.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The secondary logo is also placed in the blue cap.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The uniforms use the breathable double-knit polyester fabric, claiming the previously lighter Climate Base fabric became too heavy, once players began to sweat.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Colorado Rockies replaced their purple road pinstripes with a more traditional solid gray uniform which was unveiled at RockiesFest in Denver in January 2012.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The San Francisco Giants and Atlanta Braves added alternate uniforms to their set.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Giants wear a Sunday road game grey alternate based on the road uniforms they wore during their 1989 World Series run, with the interlocking 'SF' logo on the left chest and black neck-hoop piping.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The black piping was also incorporated into the team's normal road gray uniforms.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Braves unveiled a cream (heritage white) home alternates based on the uniforms worn in their first season in Atlanta.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The uniform has the 'Braves' wordmark without the tomahawk with the uniform number below on the left chest and navy piping.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The sleeves have a logo commemorating the Braves franchise's first season in 1876.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] A new, slightly altered Los Angeles Dodgers logo made its way to the Dodgers dugout wall at Dodger Stadium and for their "Social September" promotion in September 2011.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The baseball and flight lines have been thickened, while the "o" in the script "Dodgers" no longer has a line on the bottom left.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The home uniform script continues to use the previous script, though.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] After reviving the Northwest Green jerseys at home, the Seattle Mariners brought back their navy with teal bill caps, last worn in 2002, for Monday and Friday home contests.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Also, their navy road alternate will now have "SEATTLE" on the jersey front.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Royals unveiled minor tweaks to their light blue home alternate jersey, with all numbers and lettering now white with royal trim, and a revamped away uniform (changed to a darker blue-gray color and a revamped "Kansas City" script).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In addition, the team has dropped their light blue caps.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Cleveland Indians made minor tweaks to the home and alternate uniforms.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The white home uniform features navy collar piping and the 'Indians' script in red and navy trim, removing the white inner trim as well as the navy piping on the button lines.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The navy alternate features gray collar piping and the 'Indians' script in red and white trim, removing the navy inner trim as well as the grey piping on the button lines.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim revert to the silver halo after changing it to gold the previous year.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] They also added a sleeve patch that says 'Angels Baseball' with the foundation year (1961) separated by the current logo in between.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The logo is wrapped in a red, navy and silver circle.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This patch will be placed on all uniforms.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] As part of their 40th anniversary in Arlington, the Texas Rangers will wear replicas of the four different uniforms they have worn throughout the team's history, the most notable of which are the two uniforms worn during the ownership of then-future president of the United States George W.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] As part of their 50th anniversary, the Astros will wear throwbacks throughout the season, including a game with Colt .45s uniforms.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Red Sox and the Yankees wore 1912 throwbacks on April 20 to mark the 100th anniversary of Fenway Park.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] It marked only the second time the Yankees have worn throwbacks; the first was in 1996, when they wore New York Black Yankees uniforms at a Negro leagues tribute game in Detroit.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Red Sox and Athletics wore 1936 uniforms on May 2 at Fenway Park.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Twins wore Minneapolis Millers uniforms on June 30 in the second game of a make-up doubleheader against the Royals, who wore the uniforms of the Kansas City Blues.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Nationals wore the uniforms of the 1924 Washington Senators on July 5 against the Giants, who wore the 1924 New York Giants uniforms.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Athletics wore the PCL Oakland Oaks uniforms, and the Mariners the Rainiers, on July 8.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Brewers will wear Milwaukee Bears Negro leagues uniforms on July 28.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Diamondbacks will wear a throwback uniform on September 15.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fans decided online that their 1998 purple uniform will be worn.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The White Sox are wearing 1972 uniforms on Sundays at home this season.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Detroit Tigers and Pittsburgh Pirates wore throwback uniforms paying tribute to the Negro league baseball teams Detroit Stars and Pittsburgh Crawfords on May 19.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim and Seattle Mariners wore throwback uniforms of defunct Pacific Coast League teams Los Angeles Angels and Seattle Rainiers on May 26.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Chicago Cubs and San Francisco Giants wore 1912 throwback uniforms on June 2.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Pirates and Royals wore Negro leagues uniforms on June 9 – the Pirates, the Homestead Grays and the Royals, the Kansas City Monarchs.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Tampa Bay Rays wore 'faux-back' 1979 throwback jerseys on June 30 against the Tigers, who also wore throwback jerseys from the same year.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Due to the fact the Rays did not exist as a franchise in 1979, their uniform design was inspired from popular uniform styles such as pullovers and two-tone caps.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The San Diego Padres and New York Mets wore 1989 throwback uniforms on August 3.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Louis Cardinals and Milwaukee Brewers celebrated the 30th anniversary of the 1982 World Series by wearing throwback uniforms on August 4.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Cardinals also added a 30th anniversary patch commemorating their World Series victory, exclusive to their throwback uniforms.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The next night, the Cardinals wore their road blue uniforms against the Brewers.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Cincinnati Reds and Philadelphia Phillies wore throwback uniforms from the 1991 season on August 22.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Ironically, on June 16, 1991, the Reds and Phillies had worn 1957 uniforms at Veterans Stadium.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Cardinals wore special uniforms to commemorate their 2011 World Series win on April 13–14.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The 'STL' on the caps was gold with navy trim, while the word 'Cardinals' and the block numbers on the uniforms were gold with navy trim.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Cardinals wore them during the unfurling of their championship flag on April 13, and the presentation of the Commissioner's Trophy and World Series rings on April 14.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] 42 on April 15, the 65th anniversary of Jackie Robinson's MLB debut.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Dodgers wore a Brooklyn-era cap and batting helmet that day, as well.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Pirates and Orioles donned camouflage uniforms during Memorial Day weekend.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Brewers wore an Italian-language batting practice uniform with the word "Birrai" on July 1; their opponents Arizona Diamondbacks ('I D-Backs') also wore Italian-language uniforms.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] They also wore the Cerveceros uniforms on June 2 against the Pirates ('Piratas').
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Players wore special caps on Memorial Day and Independence Day; the Blue Jays also wore special caps on Canada Day, along with a specialized red uniform.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This year, a camouflage design was used in lieu of the American and Canadian flags.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In commemoration of the September 11 attacks, all American teams wore caps with the American flag sewn on the left; the Blue Jays sported both the American and Canadian flags on both sides of their caps.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] As part of Cinco de Mayo the San Francisco Giants ("Gigantes") and Houston Astros ("Los Astros") wore Spanish-language home uniforms for the game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] On July 6, the New York Mets ("Los Mets") wore blue Spanish-language jerseys for the game against the Chicago Cubs.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] They wore the uniforms again on August 24 against the Astros.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Chicago White Sox wore a variation of their home uniforms on September 7 against the Royals, as part of the "Halfway to St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The uniform substitutes the traditional black color for green.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Athletics and Diamondbacks wore Spanish-language uniforms in celebration of Mexican Independence Day on September 16, against the Orioles and Giants, respectively.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The A's used their primary home uniform, with "Atléticos" substituting for "Athletics", while the D-Backs used their black alternate uniform, with "Los D-Backs" substituting for the secondary "A" logo.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Florida Marlins vacated Sun Life Stadium at the end of the 2011 season and moved into Marlins Park, which was built on the site of the old Orange Bowl stadium.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The team officially adopted its new name of Miami Marlins on November 11, 2011.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The 2012 season marked the 100th anniversary of the opening of Boston's Fenway Park.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In addition, Dodger Stadium—home of the Los Angeles Dodgers—celebrated its 50th anniversary, and the Baltimore Orioles home, Oriole Park at Camden Yards, also celebrated its 20th anniversary.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The 2012 season also marked the 50th anniversary for the New York Mets and the Houston Astros, but the 51st season for both teams.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Mets began play four years after the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Giants moved west in 1958, leaving New York City with only one MLB team in the Yankees.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In 1959, New York City attorney William Shea, with support from baseball figures including former Dodgers executive Branch Rickey, proposed a third major league called the Continental League.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Houston and New York City were both among the announced CL cities.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] MLB responded to the threat by placing new franchises in several of these cities, and offered a National League franchise to the owners of the proposed New York CL team, who accepted.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] With Shea's goal of bringing a second major-league team to New York successful, he abandoned the new league, which officially folded in 1960 without ever playing a game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Mets began play in 1962 at the Giants' former home of the Polo Grounds in Manhattan, moved in 1964 to Shea Stadium (named after the aforementioned William Shea) in Queens, and opened their current home of Citi Field, adjacent to the former Shea Stadium site, in 2009.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Astros were also enfranchised as a direct response to the plans to launch the CL.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] They began play in 1962 as the Houston Colt .45s; following a dispute with Colt Firearms over revenues from souvenir sales and licensing fees, the team moved to the Astrodome in 1965 and renamed itself the Astros.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In 2000, they opened their current home, now known as Minute Maid Park.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In honor of the Astros' 50th anniversary, they donned different throwback uniforms at home on Friday night themed to each decade.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Major League Baseball enters the 6th year of seven-year contracts it signed with its broadcast partners prior to the 2007 season.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This year, Fox will televise the Saturday Game of the Week (which will be shown in prime time each week from May 19 to July 7), the All-Star Game, the National League Championship Series, and the World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TBS will show a Sunday Game of the Week, the All-Star Selection Show, all but two Division Series games, the American League Championship Series, and the new wild card elimination games.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] They will also air 10 spring training games, as well as five nationally televised games on Opening Week from April 4–6.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The MLB Network will air a national Game of the Week broadcast every Thursday and the two Division Series games not shown on TBS.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Major League Baseball International will air in syndication the All-Star Game, the ALCS, and the World Series to global markets.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Padres switched from Cox Cable-owned 4SD to a new channel called Fox Sports San Diego, which the Padres also have a minority stake in.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This is the last season of Houston Astros games on Fox Sports Houston and KTXH.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Starting next season, all games will be on Comcast SportsNet Houston, a new channel the Astros will co-own with the Houston Rockets.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Mid-Atlantic Sports Network (MASN), which broadcasts Orioles and Nationals games, became the latest network to adjust its score box to the 16:9 aspect ratio for high-definition television broadcasts.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The adjustment, which began with Fox Sports' MLB coverage in 2010, was later adopted to other networks, notably ESPN, TBS, Fox Sports Net (except Fox Sports South and some terrestrial television broadcasts produced by Fox Sports), and Root Sports during the 2011 season.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-major-league-baseball-season-p02] As of this season, only the YES Network, New England Sports Network, Comcast SportsNet, SportsNet New York and SportsTime Ohio have yet to move to the newly adjusted high definition broadcast.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The **2012 National League Championship Series** was a best-of-seven playoff in Major League Baseball’s 2012 postseason pitting the third-seeded San Francisco Giants against the defending World Series champion and fifth-seeded St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Louis Cardinals for the National League pennant and the right to play in the 2012 World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The series, the 43rd NLCS in league history, began Sunday, October 14, and ended Monday, October 22, with Fox airing all games in the United States.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] In shades of the 1996 NLCS, a series where the Cardinals blew a 3–1 series lead where they were outscored 32–1 over the final three games, the Giants came back from a 3–1 deficit and outscored the Cardinals, 20–1, over the final three games to win the series, 4–3.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] This was the third postseason meeting between the Giants and the Cardinals and also marked the first time in MLB history since the creation of the League Championship Series in 1969 that the last two World Series champions faced off against each other for the pennant.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Giants won in 2010 while the Cardinals won in 2011.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Coincidentally, the previous two postseason meetings between the two teams occurred in the NLCS, which both ended on October 14 (the day of 2012's Game 1): the Cardinals won Game 7 of the 1987 NLCS, and the Giants triumphed in the pennant-clinching Game 5 of the 2002 NLCS.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Giants would go on to sweep the Detroit Tigers in the World Series in four games.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Cardinals scored first in the second inning, with a Yadier Molina single followed by a two-run home run by David Freese.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] In the fourth inning, Daniel Descalso doubled and scored on a Pete Kozma double; Kozma then stole third base during Lance Lynn's at-bat and scored on a Jon Jay single.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] With Jay on first, Carlos Beltrán hit a two-run home run to give the Cardinals a 6–0 lead; Giants starting pitcher Madison Bumgarner was then replaced by George Kontos, who got Matt Holliday to pop out to end the inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Giants rallied back against Cardinals starting pitcher Lance Lynn in the bottom half of the fourth inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Lynn gave up a leadoff single to Marco Scutaro, who later advanced to third on a Hunter Pence single and scored on a Brandon Belt single that also advanced Pence to third.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Gregor Blanco then tripled to score Pence and Belt, and Brandon Crawford doubled to score Blanco, which cut the Cardinals' lead to 6–4.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Lynn was then replaced by Joe Kelly, who got Ángel Pagán to ground into a force play to end the inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Neither team's bullpen allowed a run for the rest of the game; additionally, the Giants' bullpen did not allow a runner into scoring position over 5+1⁄3 innings, while the Cardinals' bullpen only allowed one runner to advance into scoring position over the same number of innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Cardinals reliever Edward Mujica earned the win.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Cardinals starter Chris Carpenter gave up a home run to the leadoff hitter Ángel Pagán to give the Giants an early one-run lead.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The lead was short-lived, however, as Carpenter hit a double in the top of the second inning that scored Pete Kozma, who walked with two outs.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The game remained tied until the bottom of the fourth inning, when the Giants scored four runs, three of which were unearned amid two Cardinals errors.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Brandon Belt hit a double off Carpenter and advanced to third on Gregor Blanco's single.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Brandon Crawford then reached first base on a throwing error by first baseman Allen Craig; Belt scored on the play and Blanco advanced to second.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Crawford and Blanco then advanced to second and third, respectively, on Vogelsong's sacrifice bunt, and Pagán was walked to load the bases.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Marco Scutaro—who had been involved in a collision with Cardinals left fielder Matt Holliday in the first inning in what some termed a "questionable" slide into second base—then hit a single to left field that went between Holliday's legs, allowing Blanco, Crawford, and Pagán to score.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Giants padded their lead in the eighth inning when Ryan Theriot hit a two-RBI single with the bases loaded off Shelby Miller, scoring Blanco and Aubrey Huff.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Ryan Vogelsong pitched seven innings while Jeremy Affeldt and Sergio Romo pitched a scoreless eighth and ninth, respectively, as the Giants' 7–1 win tied the series heading to St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Giants scored first in the third inning. Ángel Pagán singled to lead off the inning, advanced to third on a Marco Scutaro double, then scored on a Pablo Sandoval groundout.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Cardinals took the lead in the bottom half of that inning, when Matt Carpenter—who had replaced Carlos Beltrán due to injury in the first inning—hit a two-run home run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Giants starter Matt Cain only allowed one baserunner over the next three innings, but the Cardinals got an insurance run in the seventh inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] After David Freese doubled with one out, Cain intentionally walked Daniel Descalso.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Pete Kozma then singled to load the bases.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Shane Robinson then grounded out, scoring Freese on the play.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] After Robinson grounded out, there was a 3-hour-and-28-minute rain delay.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] When the game resumed—with Kozma and Descalso still on base—Javier López replaced Cain and got Jon Jay to ground out to end the inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Cardinals starter Kyle Lohse earned the win with 5 2/3 innings, allowing just the one run, while Jason Motte pitched two perfect innings for the Cardinals to earn his third save of the postseason.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The second-largest crowd of the year at Busch, 47,062, saw their Redbirds win, 8–3, without the benefit of a home run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Adam Wainwright went seven strong innings, giving up only four hits and one run, a homer to Hunter Pence, walking none and striking out five, while Tim Lincecum gave up four runs in 4+2⁄3 innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Cardinals struck first in the bottom of the first when Jon Jay hit a leadoff single and Matt Carpenter walked.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Matt Holliday's RBI single and Allen Craig's sacrifice fly put St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Carpenter doubled in the fifth and scored on Holliday's single with Holliday advancing to second on the throw to home.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] One out later, Yadier Molina's RBI single made it 4–1 Cardinals.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Next inning, Daniel Descalso and Pete Kozma hit back-to-back leadoff singles off George Kontos.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] After a sacrifice bunt, Jay's two-run double off Jose Mijares made it 6–1 Cardinals.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Next inning, Craig hit a leadoff single off Guillermo Mota and scored on Molina's double.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Two outs later, Molina scored on Kozma's single off Jeremy Affeldt.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Fernando Salas pitched two innings in relief of Wainwright and, despite allowing a two-run home run to Pablo Sandoval in the ninth, held the Cardinals' lead to put them one win away from the World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Cardinals had runners on second and third with no outs early in the bottom of the second inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Giants starting pitcher Barry Zito retired Daniel Descalso and intentionally walked Pete Kozma to bring Cardinals starting pitcher Lance Lynn to the plate.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Lynn grounded into a double play, and Zito escaped the jam.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Just as he had done in Game 1, Lynn pitched three scoreless innings but then gave up four runs and could not finish the fourth inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] In that inning, with one out and Marco Scutaro and Pablo Sandoval on base after two singles, Hunter Pence grounded back to Lynn, whose throw to second base to force Sandoval hit the bag and bounced into center field, allowing Scutaro to score.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] After another out and a walk, Brandon Crawford hit a two-RBI single, and then Zito scored another run with a bunt single.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Lynn was then relieved by Joe Kelly, who finished the inning with a strikeout.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Sandoval extended the Giants' lead with a home run in the top of the eighth off Mitchell Boggs.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Zito pitched shutout ball into the bottom of the eighth inning, and the final four outs were recorded by Santiago Casilla and Sergio Romo as the Giants' 5–0 win forced a Game 6 in San Francisco.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Strong pitching by starting pitcher Ryan Vogelsong helped the Giants to a 6–1 victory.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Giants became the first team since the 2008 Boston Red Sox to come back from a 3–1 deficit to tie the series (although the 2008 Red Sox would lose Game 7), and first in the National League since the 2003 Florida Marlins.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] After Marco Scutaro drew a one-out walk in the first, Pablo Sandoval doubled over the head of Jon Jay as the center fielder got turned around fighting the sun and shadows during the twilight start.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Scutaro scored on Posey's groundout to third to give the Giants a 1–0 lead and the NL batting champion his first RBI of the series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Brandon Belt tripled to right-center leading off the second.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Gregor Blanco struck out swinging and Brandon Crawford was intentionally walked.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] With Crawford trying to steal second on the pitch, Vogelsong chopped a ball that shortstop Pete Kozma could not handle as Belt scored.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] One out later, Scutaro doubled to left to score and Sandoval singled on the 10th pitch from Chris Carpenter to score Scutaro to put the Giants ahead 5–0.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Ryan Vogelsong exceeded his career high by one with nine strikeouts, and the San Francisco Giants took a 5–1 lead over the St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The only baserunner Vogelsong allowed was a one-out walk to Matt Carpenter in the first, until Daniel Descalso's broken-bat single to center with two outs in the fifth.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Pete Kozma also singled before Vogelsong got pinch-hitter Skip Schumaker to ground out to first.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Allen Craig's single in the sixth drove home Carlos Beltrán, who doubled with two outs, for the Cardinals' only run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Chris Carpenter was replaced after allowing six hits and five runs, three unearned, in four innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Matt Carpenter replaced Matt Holliday at first base in the St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Louis lineup and batted second when the left fielder was scratched about 45 minutes before first pitch because of lower back tightness.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Allen Craig shifted from first to left field, and Beltrán slid back a spot to third in the batting order, while playing right field.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Giants got one more run in the eighth on Ryan Theriot's RBI single off Edward Mujica with two on, the run charged to Mark Rzepczynski.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The 10 unearned runs allowed by the Cardinals in the series were the most in NLCS history, according to STATS LLC.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Game 7 featured a rematch of Game 3 starters Matt Cain and Kyle Lohse.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Giants took an early lead in the first inning after consecutive singles by Ángel Pagán and Marco Scutaro followed by a Pablo Sandoval RBI groundout.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] However, the Cardinals threatened in the second inning with runners on second and third and two outs.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Cain ended the threat by inducing a Lohse line-out to a leaping Brandon Crawford.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Giants added insurance in the bottom of the second after a Cain RBI single, marking the third consecutive game in which a Giants pitcher had batted in a run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Giants jumped on Lohse in the bottom of the third, and the Cardinal starter's night was ended after he proceeded to give up a single to Scutaro, a double to Sandoval, and a walk to Posey to load the bases.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Against Joe Kelly, Hunter Pence then hit an odd double that somehow made contact with his broken bat three times, causing it to unexpectedly knuckle away from and past the shortstop Pete Kozma.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Scutaro and Sandoval scored, and center fielder Jon Jay misplayed the ball in center field, allowing Posey to score.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] After a single and walk reloaded the bases, Crawford and Pagán hit into fielder's choice plays to give the Giants a 7–0 lead.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Finally, Sandoval lined out to first baseman Allen Craig to end the five-run third.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Cain went 5+2⁄3 innings without giving up a run, and the bullpen would continue to shut out the Cardinals.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] A run-scoring double play by Aubrey Huff off Mitchell Boggs in the seventh inning and a home run by Brandon Belt in the eighth off Jason Motte added to the onslaught as the Giants surged ahead 9–0.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Under a steady downpour in the ninth inning, reliever Javier López notched the first two outs, but was lifted after two walks.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] In the sloppy conditions, closer Sergio Romo then allowed both runners to reach scoring position with a wild pitch, but ultimately got Matt Holliday to pop out to Scutaro to win the series for San Francisco.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The victory marked the first time the Giants had ever won a postseason Game 7, having previously lost Game 7 of the 1912 World Series, the 1924 World Series, the 1962 World Series, the 1987 National League Championship Series and the 2002 World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] It was also the second time in three games that the Giants staff had tossed a shutout; the Cardinals scored only one run over the final 28 innings of the series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] San Francisco also became the second club in MLB history to win six elimination games in one postseason, following the 1985 Kansas City Royals.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] The Cardinals became the first team in MLB history to play in three winner-take-all postseason games in the same year.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Meanwhile, the Giants became the first team to win both a winner-take-all Game 5 of the Division Series and a winner-take-all Game 7 in a League Championship Series in the same year.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] With three hits in the game, Series MVP Marco Scutaro finished 14-for-28 batting, tying the LCS record for hits.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Nielsen ratings showed that 31.8% of households in the St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Louis area watched the game compared with 27.5 in the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] Nationally, Nielsen found that 8.1 million viewers saw this game, a 4.9% share of households.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] (Central Time Zone) before declining as viewers switched to *Monday Night Football* or the presidential debate.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-championship-series] To date, this is the last and only Game 7 played at AT&T Park (now named Oracle Park).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The **2012 National League Division Series** were two best-of-five-game series on the National League side in Major League Baseball’s 2012 postseason to determine the participating teams in the 2012 National League Championship Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The three divisional winners and a fourth team—the winner of a one-game Wild Card playoff—played in two separate series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] This series with the Washington Nationals was their first playoff berth since moving to Washington, D.C., and the first franchise playoff berth since 1981 when they were the Montreal Expos.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] TBS carried most of the games, with some on TNT.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Wild Card Game was held on October 5, 2012.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The 2–3 format was used for best-of-five Championship Series prior to 1985 and for the Division Series from 1995 to 1997.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Both series saw the first postseason meetings between the respective clubs and both went to the maximum five games.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Giants went on to defeat the Cardinals in the NLCS, then win the 2012 World Series defeating the American League champion Detroit Tigers.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] To date, this was the last National League Division Series to not feature the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The series opened on a sunny afternoon in St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Louis, before 47,078 fans watching the Nationals' first playoff game since October 19, 1981, when they were the Montreal Expos.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] It was the first time a team from Washington, D.C., played in a postseason contest since the 1933 World Series, when the Washington Senators lost to the Giants.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Louis score without the benefit of a hit.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In Game 2, the Nationals struck first in the top of the second on Ryan Zimmerman's RBI single off Jaime Garcia, but after back-to-back leadoff singles in the bottom of the inning off him, David Freese's double and Daniel Descalso's single scored a run each.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] After a strikeout, Skip Schumaker's groundout and Jon Jay's RBI single made it 4–1 Cardinals.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Allen Craig and Descalso hit home runs in the third and fourth off Jordan Zimmermann.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Pete Kozma walked in the fourth, moved to third on a sacrifice bunt and scored on an error on Jay's ground ball.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Back-to-back home runs by Ryan Zimmerman and Adam LaRoche in the fourth off Lance Lynn made it 7–3 Cardinals.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Carlos Beltran's home run in the sixth off Mike Gonzalez made it 8–3.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Nationals scored their last run of the game in the seventh on Zimmernan's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third off Edward Mujica.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the eighth, Komza doubled with one out off Sean Burnett and scored on Jay's two-out triple, then Beltran's second home run of the game made it 11–4.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] After walking Matt Holliday, Burnett was relieved by Tom Gorzelanny, who allowed an RBI double to Craig.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Trevor Rosenthal struck out three of the four batters he faced in the ninth as the Cardinals tied the series with a 12–4 win.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Both teams combined to use 13 pitchers, with Lance Lynn working three relief innings to get the win.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Washington, D.C.'s first playoff game in 79 years was not a pleasant one for the home team.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Nationals were blown out for the second straight game and left 10 men on base—including the bases loaded in the fifth inning—and didn't even get anyone on in the last three innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Chris Carpenter ran his postseason record to 10–2 (2.88 ERA) in 16 postseason starts in 100.0 innings, in seventh place for wins, only one behind Curt Schilling (11–2, 2.23 ERA) and Greg Maddux (11–14, 3.27 ERA) for fifth place.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] He is now tied for fourth place in postseason winning percentage (.833).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Cardinals have won 13 of his 16 starts.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Louis in only his fourth start since recovering from transplanted nerve surgery on July 19, not starting a game until September 21.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] He pitched 5+2⁄3 innings without allowing a run in 106 pitches, his season high.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Edwin Jackson surrendered four runs and eight hits in five innings, allowing a two-out single to Matt Holliday in the first and subsequent RBI double to Allen Craig, then a three-run home run to Pete Kozma in the second.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Cardinals added to their lead on Daniel Descalso's sacrifice fly after a hit-by-pitch and double off Craig Stammen, who increased his ERA in the series to 11.57.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Christian Garcia walked Yadier Molina with the bases loaded in the seventh to force in another run, and Ryan Mattheus got two outs in the eighth before allowing a single, double, and two-run single to Holliday to give the Cardinals an 8–0 lead.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Fernando Salas and Joe Kelly pitched a scoreless eighth and ninth respectively to put the Cardinals one win from the NLCS.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Nationals had their backs against the wall in this must-win game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Adam LaRoche provided the first offense of the game with a homer for Washington in the bottom of the second off Kyle Lohse, but the Cardinals manufactured a run in the third inning through a walk, a sacrifice bunt, an error, and a sacrifice fly by Carlos Beltran off Ross Detwiler.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] It was 1–1 for the majority of the rest of the game, as both pitching staffs refused to blink.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Ross Detwiler pitched very well for the Nationals, tossing six innings while giving up just three hits and one run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The bullpen, in three innings, combined for eight strikeouts—after Detwiler had fanned just three—and did not give up a hit.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Louis turned in a similar performance, with Kyle Lohse pitching seven strong innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the bottom of the ninth, Jayson Werth, on the 13th pitch of a lead off at-bat against Lance Lynn, lined a homer into left field, giving the Nationals a 2–1 win and forcing a Game 5.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Louis clinched a trip to the NLCS for the second straight year.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Nationals jumped out early on off Adam Wainwright.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the first, Jayson Werth hit a leadoff double and scored on Bryce Harper's triple before Ryan Zimmerman's home run put them up 3–0.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Bryce Harper's leadoff home run in the third made it 4–0, then Zimmerman doubled before Michael Morse's home run extended the Nationals' lead to 6–0.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] With their ace Gio González on the mound, the Nationals appeared headed towards the NLCS.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the fourth inning, Matt Holliday hit an RBI double after a walk to get the Cardinals on the board.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Louis scored two more runs on a wild pitch and walk to Allen Craig, but wound up stranding the bases loaded.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the seventh, the Cardinals tacked on another run off Edwin Jackson appearing in relief on two days' rest on Holliday's RBI groundout.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Cardinals continued to chip away at the Nationals' lead when Daniel Descalso homered off Tyler Clippard to make it 6–5 Washington.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Nationals got a much-needed insurance run in the bottom of the eighth on Kurt Suzuki's RBI single off Jason Motte, and sent out Drew Storen, who had recently replaced Clippard as the team's closer, to pitch the ninth.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Storen gave up a leadoff double to Carlos Beltrán, who then advanced to third on a Matt Holliday groundout.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Allen Craig then struck out, putting the Nationals one out away from going to the NLCS for the first time in 31 years and giving Washington, D.C., its first postseason series victory since 1924.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Yadier Molina, a hero of the 2006 postseason, walked, sending up David Freese as the go-ahead run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Freese, the 2011 World Series MVP, also walked.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Descalso then hit a single, scoring Beltrán and pinch-runner Adron Chambers to tie the game at seven.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] After Descalso stole second, Pete Kozma hit a single, which scored Freese and Descalso and made it 9–7 St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Washington went down in order in the bottom of the ninth against Jason Motte, sending the Cardinals to the NLCS for the second year in a row.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] To date, six runs is the biggest deficit a team has overcome to win a winner-take-all postseason game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Matt Cain and Johnny Cueto faced off against each other for the first time in 2012.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Everyone expected a pitchers' duel from the two right-handed aces.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the top of the first, Brandon Belt made an amazing catch, leaping over the fence in foul territory and into the crowd, but holding on for the second out to help Cain pitch a 1–2–3 inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the bottom of the first, however, after Cueto struck out Ángel Pagán and then got ahead in the count 0–2 on Marco Scutaro, Cueto left the game with back spasms.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] LeCure got out of a bases-loaded jam in the second inning by getting Cain to line out to deep right.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the top of the third, Brandon Phillips put the Reds up 2–0 with a two-run home run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] After a Jay Bruce home run in the fourth, Buster Posey's home run leading off the sixth off Mat Latos put the Giants on the board.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Then, Gregor Blanco bunted with two out.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Scott Rolen picked up the ball and threw it away, but Phillips made a great diving stop to keep Blanco off second and the Giants from scoring anymore.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the ninth, the Reds added two runs off Santiago Casilla with two on via an RBI single from Phillips and a passed ball by Posey.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the bottom of the inning, Aroldis Chapman allowed the Giants to load the bases on a single and two walks and threw a two-out wild pitch that allowed a run to score, but struck out Posey to end the game and seal the Reds' 5–2 win to take a 1–0 series lead.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] This was the first Reds postseason win since 1995, breaking a seven-game losing streak in the postseason.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Reds starter Bronson Arroyo gave up just two hits in seven innings, while walking one and striking out four.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Hoover and José Arredondo combined for two scoreless innings out of the bullpen.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In contrast, the Giants' pitching was disappointing, as Madison Bumgarner surrendered seven hits and four runs while working just four innings, including a home run by Ryan Ludwick in the second.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the fourth, Bumgarner allowed two leadoff singles, then one out later, an RBI single to Scott Rolen and two-run single to Ryan Hanigan.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Six relievers followed Bumgarner, including Tim Lincecum, who worked two scoreless innings after being demoted to the bullpen, and Guillermo Mota, who surrendered three hits and two runs in just 2⁄3 of an inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Reds put the game out of reach in the eighth when a leadoff single and subsequent walk was followed by Jay Bruce's two-run double off Jose Mijares.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] After Santiago Casilla got one out, Hanigan's single, Drew Stubbs's triple, and Brandon Phillips's double off Mota scored a run each.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Giants were now in a two-games-to-none hole, while Cincinnati was just one win away from going to the NLCS for the first time in 17 years, with three chances to clinch the series at home.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In contrast to Game 2's blowout, Game 3 was a tightly contested affair that came down right to the wire.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Cincinnati attacked first on Jay Bruce's RBI single in the first inning off Ryan Vogelsong, scoring Zack Cozart.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] That would be practically it for the Reds' offense, as the Giants' pitching composed themselves to give up just one hit the rest of the way.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Homer Bailey, who had pitched a no-hitter just two starts before, was flirting with another one, not giving up a hit through 5+2⁄3 innings before Marco Scutaro broke it up with a two-strike single.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] That was the only hit the Giants would get in regulation, as Bailey was brilliant, pitching seven innings while striking out ten.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] However, the Giants still managed to score a run in the third inning with a hit by pitch, a walk, a sacrifice bunt, and a sacrifice fly.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Neither team came close to scoring after that until the 10th inning, when Buster Posey and Hunter Pence got back to back singles to kick off the inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Jonathan Broxton settled down after that to strike out the next two hitters.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] After the runners advanced on a passed ball, the usually sure-handed Scott Rolen bobbled a ground ball hit by Joaquín Árias, allowing Posey to score.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Reds went down quietly in the 10th inning as the Giants avoided the sweep.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In Game 4, needing another win to keep their season alive, the Giants' offense finally came to life. Ángel Pagán hit the second pitch of the night, from emergency starter Mike Leake, over the right field wall for a lead-off home run, the first in Giants postseason history.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Pitching for the Giants, Barry Zito struggled early, allowing a two-out single to Joey Votto, then walking three consecutive Reds hitters in the bottom of the first to force in a run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the second inning, Gregor Blanco hit a two-run home run to give the Giants a 3–1 lead.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Zito continued to struggle, needing 76 pitches to complete just under three innings of work and allowing a home run to Ryan Ludwick in the third that made it 3–2 Giants.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] George Kontos relieved Zito that inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the fifth, Back-to-back doubles by Joaquín Árias and Pagán off Leake, followed by a Pablo Sandoval sacrifice fly off Sam LeCure gave the Giants a 5–2 lead.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Tim Lincecum struck out six batters in 4+1⁄3 innings for the Giants, ultimately getting the win.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Santiago Casilla closed out the game, and the Giants avoided elimination for the second straight night, setting up a decisive Game 5.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Reds' Mat Latos and the Giants' Matt Cain were locked in a pitchers' duel for four innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the top of the fifth, Brandon Crawford tripled home Gregor Blanco, who singled to lead off, to open the scoring.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Angel Pagan then reached on an error by Zack Cozart, allowing Crawford to score the second run of the inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] After a walk to Scutaro, Sandoval singled to load the bases.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Buster Posey then crushed a 2–2 pitch from Latos off the facing of the second deck for a grand slam and a 6–0 lead.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the bottom of the fifth, a hit-by-pitch and single was followed by Brandon Phillips's two-run double.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Next inning, Ryan Ludwick's leadoff home run made it 6–3.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] In the ninth, a one-out walk and single was followed by Ludwik's RBI single.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Reds brought the tying run to the plate in the sixth, seventh, and eighth innings, and the winning run to the plate in the ninth inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] With two men on and the Giants clinging to a two-run lead, Sergio Romo retired Jay Bruce on a harmless fly ball to left after a 12-pitch duel.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Romo then settled down and struck out Scott Rolen (in what would be the final at-bat of his Hall of Fame career) to give the Giants the victory.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Giants became the second National League team to rally from an 0–2 Division Series deficit to advance to the Championship Series (the other being the 1981 Los Angeles Dodgers) and first in Major League Baseball to advance by winning three games on the road.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] Cincinnati joined the 1984 Chicago Cubs and 1981 Houston Astros as the only National League teams to blow a 2–0 lead in a best–of–five series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] This series also joined the 2010 ALDS matchup between the Texas Rangers and the Tampa Bay Rays as the second MLB postseason series in which the road team won every game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-national-league-division-series] The Reds to date have yet to win a postseason game at Great American Ball Park (0–4) and a six-game home losing streak in the postseason, losing their last two at Riverfront Stadium/Cinergy Field in the 1995 NLCS.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] The **San Francisco Giants** are an American baseball team.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] Their **2012 season** marked their 130th year in Major League Baseball, as well as their 55th year in San Francisco since their move from New York following the 1957 season, and the 13th at AT&T Park.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] The Giants finished with a record of 94–68.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] They finished in first place in the National League West, and defeated the Cincinnati Reds in five games in the NLDS thereby becoming the first National League team (eighth in MLB history) to come back from a 2–0 deficit in a best-of-five series by sweeping three games in the opponent's park.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] Louis Cardinals in seven games after overcoming a 3–1 deficit in the NLCS and advancing to the World Series to face the Detroit Tigers.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] They swept the Tigers in four games to win their second World Series title in three years.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] The season also saw Giants pitcher Matt Cain throw a perfect game on June 13, 2012.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] The San Francisco Giants defeated the Cincinnati Reds to advance to the 2012 National League Championship Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] The San Francisco Giants defeated the St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] Louis Cardinals for the National League title.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] Wednesday, October 17, 2012 at Busch Stadium in St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] Thursday, October 18, 2012 at Busch Stadium in St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] Friday, October 19, 2012 at Busch Stadium in St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] The Giants swept the Detroit Tigers 4–0 to win the World Series Championship.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-san-francisco-giants-season] The sweep marks as the franchise's first-ever in a playoffs or championship while in San Francisco.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The **2012 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 2012 season.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The 108th edition of the World Series, the series was a best-of-seven playoff between the National League (NL) champion San Francisco Giants and the American League (AL) champion Detroit Tigers; the Giants won in a four-game sweep.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] This marked the Giants' seventh World Series title in franchise history, their second in San Francisco (they won five in New York), and their second in a three-year period (2010–2012).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Their World Series sweep was the first by an NL team since the Cincinnati Reds swept the Oakland Athletics in the 1990 series and the first NL sweep not by the Reds since 1963, when the Los Angeles Dodgers swept the New York Yankees.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] This was also the first World Series since 1988 to feature both of that year's League MVPs (Miguel Cabrera for the AL and Buster Posey for the NL).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants' Pablo Sandoval, who in Game 1 tied a record by hitting three home runs in one World Series game — two off Tigers' ace pitcher Justin Verlander — was named the World Series Most Valuable Player (MVP).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The San Francisco Giants held home field advantage for the World Series due to the NL winning the 2012 MLB All-Star Game: San Francisco hosted Games 1 and 2, and would have hosted Games 6 and 7 if these had been necessary to decide the Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The 2012 series began on Wednesday, October 24, at AT&T Park in San Francisco, California and ended on Sunday, October 28, at Comerica Park in Detroit, Michigan, with the conclusion of the fourth game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers advanced to the World Series after sweeping the Yankees in four games during the American League Championship Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants advanced to the World Series after winning the National League Championship Series four games to three over the St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Louis Cardinals, the 2011 World Series winners.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] As of 2025, this is the most recent World Series to end in a sweep; 13 World Series have been played in this span.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In accordance with the standard since 2003, the outcome of the All-Star Game decided whether the American or National League would hold home field advantage in the World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The National League All-Star Team won the 2012 All-Star Game, played on July 10 in Kansas City, Missouri, by a score of 8–0.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Representatives of both the Giants and the Tigers played key roles in the outcome.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Giant players scored and/or drove in seven of the NL All-Star team's eight runs.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The NL scored five runs in the first, all yielded by a Tiger, ace Justin Verlander.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Pablo Sandoval would hit a triple, and Melky Cabrera—who would wind up the All-Star Game MVP—hit a home run during the game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants finished the regular season atop the National League West with a 94–68 record, eight games ahead of the second place Los Angeles Dodgers and good enough to secure the #3 seed in the NL.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] They defeated the second-seeded Cincinnati Reds in the National League Division Series, a best-of-five series, in five games.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] They then defeated the defending 2011 World Series champions, the fifth-seeded St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Louis Cardinals, in a seven-game series to capture the National League pennant.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The manner in which the Giants defeated the Reds and then the Cardinals created some historical firsts.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Because of the addition of a wildcard game, the National League Division Series between the Giants and Reds began with two games in San Francisco.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Cincinnati, who posted a better won-lost record than the Giants, hosted the final three games.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants lost the first two games at home in San Francisco, yet won the last three on the road.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants became the first major league team to win three straight road games in a best-of-five playoff series after losing the first two games at home.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the second round of the playoffs, the National League Championship Series, they came back from a three-games-to-one deficit to defeat the St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Through this playoff course, the 2012 Giants became the first National League team and the second team in American major league baseball history (after the 1985 Kansas City Royals) to win six consecutive playoff games in which they had faced elimination.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] This was the Giants' 22nd NL pennant overall, their fifth as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Their World Series berth was their second in three years (since 2010, when they defeated the Texas Rangers in five games).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] This was the fifth World Series in which the Giants faced a team from the American League Central Division (1917, 1924, 1933, 1954).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] San Francisco's notable preseason acquisitions were outfielders Melky Cabrera and Ángel Pagán.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Cabrera set the Giants' franchise record for hits in the month of May, with 51, and Pagán set the San Francisco Giants record for triples in a season, with 15.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] On August 15, Major League Baseball meted a 50-game suspension upon Cabrera for his use of a banned substance.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] At the time, his 159 hits led both leagues, his .346 batting average measured second in the NL, and he had received the 2012 All-Star Game MVP.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The suspension expired after the NLDS, but the Giants opted not to add him to the team's NLCS or World Series rosters.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] All-Star Buster Posey finished the regular season with a .336 batting average to win the 2012 NL batting championship.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the World Series, he would go on to catch every inning, including the shutouts in Game 2 and Game 3.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] He would, in the World Series, not allow any baserunners to advance by either passed ball, stolen base, or wild pitch.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] He would begin a double play in Game 1 and execute an important tag play in Game 2.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Earlier in the regular season, starting pitcher Matt Cain threw the first perfect game in Giants history, and the 22nd in American major league history, on June 13.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] He would start Game 4 of the World Series, which the Giants would win to clinch.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Relief pitcher Sergio Romo contributed to team success by converting 14 out of 15 save opportunities after an injury sidelined closer Brian Wilson a few days after the season began.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Romo converted three saves in the World Series, including the Game 4 clincher, which ended with Romo striking out the 2012 American League MVP.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Midseason addition Marco Scutaro ended the regular season with a .306 batting average and a 20-game hitting streak.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In October, Scutaro tied a League Championship Series record with 14 hits (and a .500 average) against the Cardinals, and he received the NLCS MVP.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the World Series, his Game 4 tenth-inning single drove home a run that gave the Giants a lead the team would not relinquish.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Bruce Bochy made his third World Series appearance as a manager, his second with the Giants.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Bochy led San Francisco to the 2010 title.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Before that, he led the 1998 San Diego Padres to the World Series, where the New York Yankees swept.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Bochy would win his second World Series title.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Bochy's starting rotation for the 2012 World Series: Barry Zito in Game 1, Madison Bumgarner in Game 2, Ryan Vogelsong in Game 3 and Matt Cain in Game 4.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers finished the regular season atop the American League Central, with 88 wins and 74 losses.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers repeated as champions of this division, having also won it in 2011.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] This was their first repeat title in the divisional-play era (i.e., since 1969).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The last time, before 2011–2012, that the Tigers franchise had made consecutive playoff appearances was 1934–1935.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers entered the postseason as the third seed in the AL, and defeated the second-seeded Oakland Athletics in the American League Division Series three games to two.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers then captured their 11th American League pennant, sweeping the top-seeded New York Yankees four games to none in the American League Championship Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] This World Series berth was their first since 2006, when the St.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Louis Cardinals defeated them four games to one.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers entered the World Series as heavy favorites to win the title, despite the Giants having home-field advantage and the better regular season record.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The 2012 Tigers became the fourth team to accomplish a four-game sweep in an ALCS.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The three other teams to do so (1988 Oakland A's, 1990 Oakland A's, and 2006 Detroit Tigers) did not win the World Series, and the 2012 Tigers would, in the 2012 World Series, continue this trend.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Pitcher Justin Verlander (17–8) led the American League in strikeouts with 239.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Max Scherzer (16–7) finished second in the AL with 231 strikeouts.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] During the 2012 season, pitcher Doug Fister set an AL record by striking out nine consecutive batters.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Miguel Cabrera became the first player in 45 years (since Carl Yastrzemski in 1967) to win the Triple Crown.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Miguel Cabrera compiled a .330 average, hit 44 home runs, and had 139 RBIs, all of which led the American League.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the 2012 ALCS, Cabrera extended his hitting streak in LCS games to 17, a major league LCS record.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] (Cabrera made ten hits in seven games with the Florida Marlins in the 2003 NLCS, eight hits in six games with the Tigers in the 2011 ALCS, and five hits in the Tigers' 2012 ALCS sweep.) Including this season, Miguel Cabrera has played in exactly 17 LCS games.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Miguel Cabrera would compile a .231 batting average for, and make the last out of, the 2012 World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In January 2012, prior to the start of the season, the Tigers signed first baseman Prince Fielder to a nine-year, $214 million contract.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the 2012 World Series, Prince Fielder would manage only one hit, a single, in 14 at-bats.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Manager Jim Leyland made his third trip to the World Series, and his second with the Tigers (he also managed them in 2006).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] He managed the 1997 Florida Marlins to a seven-game victory in the World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Leyland's starting rotation for the 2012 World Series: Verlander in Game 1, Doug Fister in Game 2, Aníbal Sánchez in Game 3, and Scherzer in Game 4.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In Game 1 of the World Series, Verlander would not fare much better against Giant bats than he had in the All-Star Game; allowing five earned runs in four innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants' Pablo Sandoval was named the MVP of the series after hitting .500 with three home runs.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Gerry Davis, as senior umpire, served as crew chief for the six-man crew.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] With his work in this Series, Davis set a new record for postseason games umpired in American major league history, with 115.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Fellow regular-season crew chiefs Brian Gorman and Joe West assisted Davis, along with Fieldin Culbreth, Dan Iassogna and Brian O'Nora.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants jumped out to a 6–0 lead, scoring in four of the first five innings of Game 1, en route to an 8–3 victory.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Pablo Sandoval went four-for-four, driving in four runs on three home runs.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] He joined Babe Ruth (in 1926 and 1928), Reggie Jackson (in 1977) and Albert Pujols (in 2011) as the only players to ever hit three home runs in one World Series game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Sandoval became the first to hit three homers in Game 1 of a World Series and homer in his first three plate appearances.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Tigers ace pitcher Justin Verlander lasted only four innings, giving up five Giant runs.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Sandoval's first two homers came off Verlander, a two-out home run in the first and two-run home run in the third after Angel Pagan doubled with two outs and scored on Marco Scutaro's single.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Sandoval's third home run came in the fifth off Al Alburquerque.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] San Francisco starting pitcher Barry Zito allowed only one run in 5+2⁄3 innings, and drove in a run with a fourth-inning single.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The one run came in the sixth when Austin Jackson doubled to lead off and scored on Miguel Cabrera's single.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants scored their final two runs in the seventh inning off Tiger relief pitcher José Valverde, who failed to convert saves in previous stages of the postseason.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Pagan doubled with one out, then scored on Scutaro's single.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] After Sandoval singled, Scutaro scored on Buster Posey's single.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the top of the ninth, Jhonny Peralta hit a two-run home run off George Kontos to cut the lead to 8–3, but Jeremy Affeldt came in relief of Kontos and got Ramon Santiago to ground out for the final out of the game to give the Giants a 1–0 series lead.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] After Zito allowed a run on three hits in the sixth inning, Tim Lincecum relieved him.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Lincecum pitched 2+1⁄3 perfect innings, striking out five.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Three Cy Young Award winners (Lincecum, Verlander and Zito) pitched in Game 1, the first time this has happened since Game 3 of the 1983 World Series, when Jim Palmer relieved Mike Flanagan, in a contest against Steve Carlton.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] A shutout win in Game 2 gave the Giants a two-games-to-none lead in the Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the top of the second, with Prince Fielder on first, Delmon Young lined a double into the left field corner.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Tiger third base coach Gene Lamont waved Fielder home, but with accurate throws by left fielder Gregor Blanco and second baseman Marco Scutaro, catcher Buster Posey tagged out Fielder in a close play at the plate.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the bottom of the second, Doug Fister was struck in the head by a Blanco line drive but stayed in the game, pitching out of a bases-loaded jam.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Game 2 remained scoreless until the bottom of the seventh.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Hunter Pence led off with a single, Brandon Belt drew a walk, then Blanco executed a perfect bunt down the third base line.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The ball came to rest just fair, halfway between third base and home, allowing Blanco to reach safely while both runners advanced.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] With the bases loaded and nobody out, Brandon Crawford grounded into a double play, scoring Hunter Pence.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] This was the only run Fister allowed in six sharp innings, pitching well despite the second inning scare.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the eighth, with the bases loaded and one out, Pence hit a sacrifice fly to right field, scoring Ángel Pagán with the second and final Giant run of the game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Madison Bumgarner pitched seven shutout innings, yielding only two hits and striking out eight, for the win.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants' 2–0 victory in Game 3 was the team's second straight shutout.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Matching the 2010 Giants team that also recorded two shutouts in the World Series, San Francisco became the first team since the 1966 Baltimore Orioles to record back-to-back World Series shutouts.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] (The 1966 Orioles, who threw three straight shutouts in Games 2–4, also swept the World Series, defeating the Los Angeles Dodgers.) The 2012 Giants became the first NL team to do so since the 1919 Cincinnati Reds, who threw back-to-back shutouts against the Chicago White Sox.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] These were the first back-to-back postseason shutouts for the franchise since 1917, where the New York Giants ultimately lost to the Chicago White Sox.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The only runs of the game came in the Giant half of the second inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] A one-out triple off the bat of Gregor Blanco scored Hunter Pence from third.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] A two-out single by Brandon Crawford then scored Blanco.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Those were the only runs Tigers starter Aníbal Sánchez allowed in seven otherwise good innings with eight strikeouts, but it was enough to saddle him with the loss.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] San Francisco starter Ryan Vogelsong pitched 5+2⁄3 shutout innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Detroit loaded the bases with one out in the fifth inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Then, Vogelsong threw a pitch near the hands of the next batter, Miguel Cabrera, which induced a pop fly to end the inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] As in Game 1, Tim Lincecum relieved the Giants' starter, and pitched 2+1⁄3 scoreless innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] As in Game 2, Sergio Romo converted a save, his second of three in the Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Marco Scutaro's RBI single in the top of the tenth, which allowed Ryan Theriot to score, proved the difference in the Giants' 4–3 victory.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] With the Game 4 victory, the Giants took the 2012 World Series, four games to none.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] San Francisco scored the first run of the game, in the top of the second inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] With one out, Brandon Belt tripled off starter Max Scherzer to right field, scoring Hunter Pence.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Belt was stranded at third after a groundout and a flyout.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the third inning, Detroit took its first and only lead of the series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Austin Jackson walked and advanced to second on a sacrifice bunt by Quintin Berry.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Miguel Cabrera then hit a high fly ball off Matt Cain towards right field, Hunter Pence had a chance to catch it but a strong wind drifted the ball out for a two-run home run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The shot snapped what was a 20-inning scoreless streak for the Tigers.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants regained the lead in the sixth inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Scutaro hit a ground ball down the third-base line that Detroit third baseman Cabrera could not field cleanly, resulting in an infield hit.Buster Posey then hit a two-run home run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Posey's shot stayed just inside the left-field pole as it carried out.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the bottom of the same inning, Delmon Young tied the game with a home run to right, off Giant pitcher Matt Cain, that landed over the fence in right-center.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] However, this was the last hit for the Tigers in the game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Strong relief pitching sent the game into extra innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] After relieving Scherzer in the seventh with one out, Tigers relievers Drew Smyly and Octavio Dotel combined to shut out the Giants for two innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] After a leadoff walk in the bottom of the eighth, Giant pitcher Jeremy Affeldt struck out the heart of the Tigers batting order.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the top of the ninth, Tiger pitcher Phil Coke struck out three consecutive Giant batters.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Coke set a World Series record by striking out seven consecutive batters, dating back to his appearances in Games 2 and 3.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Affeldt and Santiago Casilla combined for a scoreless bottom of the ninth.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the top of the 10th, Ryan Theriot ended Coke's strikeout streak, leading off with a single to right.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] A sacrifice bunt by Brandon Crawford moved Theriot to second. Ángel Pagán struck out.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Then Scutaro served a single in front of center-fielder Austin Jackson, which scored the decisive run.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Closer Sergio Romo struck out the side in the bottom of the 10th.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Series ended with umpire Brian O'Nora calling a third strike on Miguel Cabrera.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] After throwing Cabrera several consecutive sliders, Romo threw a fastball that backed into Cabrera's zone, which may have surprised the batter.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Because they won the Series away from their home field, the Giants accepted the World Series Championship Trophy and the World Series MVP award in their locker room.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] (Incidentally, the franchise clinched its last four World Series victories away from home.) The Giants' unexpected sweep of the Tigers was deemed as a significant upset by the media.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In the United States, Fox televised the games, with Joe Buck calling play-by-play in his 15th World Series, and Tim McCarver handling color commentary for his 23rd World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Ken Rosenthal also appeared on the Fox telecasts as a field reporter, with Erin Andrews and Chris Myers joining him for select games.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] MLB International syndicated its own telecast of the series, with announcers Gary Thorne and Rick Sutcliffe, to various networks outside the U.S.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Additionally, the American Forces Network and Canadian Forces Radio and Television carried the games to U.S. and Canadian service personnel stationed around the globe.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Fox Deportes carried the Series in Spanish on American cable and satellite TV.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] However, on August 24, Tribune removed Fox-affiliate WTIC-TV from Cablevision systems in Connecticut, causing viewers to miss Games 1 and 2 of the series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] An agreement between Cablevision and Tribune was reached on October 26, the day before Game 3.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] According to Nielsen Media Research, the four-game series on Fox averaged a record-low 7.6 rating and 12 share.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The previous low was an 8.4 rating for both the 2008 and the 2010 World Series, which each went five games.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The 6.1 rating in Game 3 matched the lowest rating for any World Series game with Game 3 in 2008; that year, a rain delay moved the start of the game to after 10 p.m. on the East Coast with the game not ending until 1:47 a.m.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Hurricane Sandy contributed to the low number of viewers as most residents on the East Coast were preparing for the storm's arrival during the series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] ESPN Radio broadcast the World Series nationally, with Dan Shulman and Orel Hershiser working their second consecutive World Series together.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] ESPN Deportes Radio aired the Series for Spanish language listeners, with Ernesto Jerez and Guillermo Celis announcing.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Locally, the two teams' flagship stations broadcast the series with their respective announcing crews.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Due to contractual obligations, the non-flagship stations on the teams' radio networks carried the ESPN Radio broadcasts of the games, although the local broadcasts were also available on XM Satellite Radio and to Gameday Audio subscribers at MLB.com.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Beyond the United States telecast on Fox, the series aired widely overseas via MLB International, which produced a separate world feed with Gary Thorne and Rick Sutcliffe on commentary.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] American and Canadian service members also received coverage through the American Forces Network and Canadian Forces Radio and Television, while Fox Deportes provided a Spanish-language telecast in the U.S.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] A cable-carriage dispute in the New York tri‑state region briefly affected access for some viewers: Tribune’s dispute with Cablevision blacked out Fox affiliate WTIC‑TV for part of the series before an agreement was reached on October 26, the day before Game 3.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers became only the third team to be swept in the World Series after sweeping the League Championship Series (LCS), joining the 1990 Oakland Athletics and the 2007 Colorado Rockies with this distinction.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] For the fourth time since 1985, when the MLB postseason expanded the LCS to a best of 7, the World Series saw a team who swept its LCS face a team who won a LCS Game 7.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The previous three times, 1988, 2006, and 2007, the Game 7 pennant-winner prevailed.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The next time it would happen would be in 2025, though in that case it would be the sweeper that prevailed.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The 2012 World Series was the first since 1954 to feature the batting champions from each league, Buster Posey of the Giants and Miguel Cabrera of the Tigers (the 1954 Series showcased Willie Mays of the New York Giants and Bobby Ávila of the Cleveland Indians).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Cabrera and Posey had been voted the MVP of their respective leagues (announced and awarded, as usual, after the World Series), making this the first World Series since 1988 to feature both league MVPs (1988 saw the Oakland Athletics' Jose Canseco and the Los Angeles Dodgers' Kirk Gibson meet).
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants became the first team since the 1966 Baltimore Orioles and the first NL team since the 1919 Cincinnati Reds to achieve consecutive shutouts in the World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] With the Giants winning Game 4 in extra innings to win the series, they became the eighth team to win a World Series-clinching game in extra innings and the first to do so since the 1997 Florida (now Miami) Marlins clinched the series in Game 7 in 11 innings.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] They were the first Giants team to do so since Game 5 of the 1933 World Series against the Washington Senators (now Minnesota Twins) in Washington when the Giants were in New York.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] After sweeping this series 4–0, Bruce Bochy became the fourth World Series Manager to be on a winning side and losing side of a sweep, having lost in a four-game sweep against the New York Yankees as the San Diego Padres manager in 1998.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Miller Huggins, Walter Alston and Tony La Russa were the other three.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] As the Giants represented the National League during the 1912 World Series (though at the time they were based in New York), the Giants became the first team to play in the World Series a century after an appearance.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Red Sox would later accomplish this feat in 2018.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] An estimated crowd of over 1 million people attended a Halloween Day victory parade along Market Street in San Francisco.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Giants failed to defend their World Series championship in 2013.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] San Francisco led the National League West early in the season, but critical injuries (including the loss of Pagan for three months) and subpar play on both ends doomed the Giants.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] They were eliminated from the playoff race on September 11, 2013, becoming the second defending World Series champion in three years to not make the postseason, after the 2011 Giants.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In 2014, the Giants would, again, win the World Series and thereby continue their even-years streak of pennants and World Championships (2010, 2012, and 2014) .
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers would win the American League Central division championship for the third straight season in 2013, marking the first season since 1909 that the Tigers won three consecutive regular season titles.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers lost the 2013 ALCS to the eventual champions Boston Red Sox in six games, which was also Jim Leyland's final season as manager.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In 2014, under new manager Brad Ausmus, they won their fourth-straight division title, but lost the ALDS to the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers soon fell into rebuilding mode for the next several seasons, bottoming out with a 47–114 mark in 2019.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Miguel Cabrera, the last Tigers player remaining from the 2012 team, retired after the 2023 season.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The Tigers would not make the postseason again until the following season, in 2024.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In 2017, the two teams continued to be linked together, as they finished with the worst two records in Major League Baseball that season.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] 2012 Detroit Tigers co-aces Justin Verlander and Max Scherzer faced off in the World Series seven years later in 2019.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Scherzer, then with the Washington Nationals, bested Verlander's Houston Astros in seven games, although they never pitched against each other.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Mid-rotation starter Anibal Sanchez also pitched in the 2019 World Series for the Nationals.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Verlander did win a World Series ring with the Astros two years earlier, and added a second in 2022.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Rick Porcello, the Tigers fourth starter in 2012, later won a World Series with the 2018 Boston Red Sox.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Drew Smyly, who pitched out of the bullpen for two games in the World Series but served as a fifth starter during the regular season prior to Sanchez's acquisition, later won a World Series for the 2021 Atlanta Braves.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In terms of position players, Quintin Berry later won a World Series, serving primarily as a pinch-runner for the 2013 Red Sox, who defeated the Cardinals in the Fall Classic in six games.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Verlander and Scherzer were briefly re-united in 2023 when Verlander signed a record free-agent contract with the New York Mets.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] There had been rumors in Detroit that the two aces did not get along, but the rumors were never confirmed or denied.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Verlander entered 2023 at age 40, while Scherzer would turn 38 in July, making them two of the oldest pitchers to ever start together in a rotation.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] At a combined $86.6 M, they were also the two most expensive pitchers to ever head a rotation, as well.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] The reunion would not last, however, and the Mets traded both Scherzer and Verlander to in-state rivals Texas Rangers and Houston Astros respectively, after struggling to begin the season.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Ironically, both the Astros and Rangers met in the 2023 ALCS, and like in the 2019 World Series, neither pitcher opposed each other in a game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] Ultimately, Scherzer's Rangers bested Verlander's Astros in seven games, again with the road team winning every game.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] At the end of his career, Verlander later pitched for the San Francisco Giants.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] This was the last World Series to feature AL and NL Most Valuable Players for the regular season until the 2024 World Series, which featured AL MVP Aaron Judge and NL MVP Shohei Ohtani.
[src:brandon-crawford/2012-world-series] In addition, this was the last World Series sweep.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He was the sixth player in MLB history to hit a grand slam in his first MLB game, and the first shortstop to hit a grand slam in an MLB postseason game.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He is a three-time All-Star (2015, 2018, and 2021), four-time Gold Glove Award winner (2015–2017, and 2021), two-time Wilson Defensive Player of the Year Award winner (2012 and 2016), and won the Silver Slugger Award at shortstop in 2015.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford has played the most games at shortstop for the Giants in franchise history, and at the end of the 2022 season was 2nd of all active players in games played at shortstop.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] After 13 seasons with the Giants, Crawford signed with the St.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Louis Cardinals in 2024, where he spent one season before announcing his retirement on November 27, 2024.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Brandon Michael Crawford was born on January 21, 1987, in Mountain View, California.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] His family lived in Menlo Park before they moved to Pleasanton when he was in elementary school.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He grew up a San Francisco Giants fan, and his family purchased season tickets and a commemorative brick in Willie Mays Plaza outside AT&T Park when the ballpark opened in 2000.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford attended Foothill High School in Pleasanton, where he was a three-sport athlete: football, basketball, and baseball.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He was the starting quarterback for the Foothill Falcons and graduated in the class of 2005.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford attended the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA), where he was a physiological sciences major.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He played baseball for the UCLA Bruins from 2006 to 2008 and helped lead the team to the NCAA Regionals in three consecutive seasons, the first time in school history.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford was named the team's MVP in 2006 and 2007, and was named to the All-Pac-10 Conference team in 2007.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In the summer of 2007, he played for the Orleans Cardinals of the Cape Cod Baseball League.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He also played in the Northwoods League for the Mankato MoonDogs in 2005 before he attended UCLA.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He helped lead the United States national team to the title in the 2006 International University Sports Federation (FISU) World Championship.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] The San Francisco Giants selected Crawford in the fourth round, with the 117th overall selection, of the 2008 MLB draft, and he signed for a $375,000 signing bonus.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford started his first full season as a professional with the High–A San Jose Giants in 2009.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 25 games, he hit .371 with six home runs and 17 RBI, good enough for a slugging percentage of .600 and 1.045 OPS.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In May, Crawford was promoted to the Double-A Connecticut Defenders, where he spent the rest of the season, batting .258/.294/.365 with four home runs in 108 games.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 2010, Crawford opened the season in Double–A (now with the Richmond Flying Squirrels) and earned an Eastern League mid-season All-Star nod, batting .241/.337/.375 in 79 games before suffering a broken hand in early July, which sidelined Crawford for nearly two months.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] When he recovered, he was assigned back to San Jose for the remainder of the season.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He was ranked the sixth-best prospect in the Giants' organization by *Baseball America* heading into 2011.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 2011, Crawford was invited to spring training but was set back by a broken finger suffered in the final week, and started the season in San Jose while he recovered.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] With the Triple–A Fresno Grizzlies, Crawford batted .234/.291/.327 in 107 at-bats.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In the AFL, he was named to the AFL All-Prospect Team.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] The Giants promoted Crawford to the major leagues for the first time on May 26, 2011, following injuries to Buster Posey, Mike Fontenot, and Darren Ford.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford made his MLB debut on May 27 against the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] His first MLB hit came in his third at bat of the game, and was a grand slam off the Brewers' Shaun Marcum.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He joined Bobby Bonds and Brian Dallimore as the only Giants whose first career MLB hit was a grand slam; he also became the sixth player in MLB history and the second player in Giants history along with Bobby Bonds to hit a grand slam in his first game.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On July 31, the Giants optioned Crawford to their Triple-A affiliate, the Fresno Grizzlies, after the Giants acquired shortstop Orlando Cabrera.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] The Giants were 23–18 with Crawford as a starter, but he was hitting only .190.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford was recalled in September when MLB rosters expanded to 40 players.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 2012, Crawford was named the team's opening day shortstop, in which he batted 8th in the lineup.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He batted .248 with four home runs, 26 doubles, and 45 RBI in 143 games.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On July 20, Crawford hit his second career grand slam and drove in 5 runs as the Giants defeated the Philadelphia Phillies 7–2.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford was praised for his defense during the 2012 postseason, which culminated in a 4–0 sweep of the Detroit Tigers in the 2012 World Series.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford ranked third among NL shortstops in Defensive Runs Saved at +12, and was recognized with the Wilson Defensive Player of the Year Award at shortstop.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford was the Giants' starting shortstop for 2013, with Joaquín Árias as his backup.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 149 games on the year, he hit .248/.311/.363 with nine home runs and 43 RBI.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 153 games, Crawford batted .246 and set career highs with ten home runs and 69 RBIs.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On April 13, Crawford hit a tenth inning, walk-off home run against Rex Brothers of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In the 2014 postseason, Crawford led all Giants with 9 RBIs.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In the fourth inning of the NL Wild Card Game between the Giants and Pittsburgh Pirates, Crawford hit a grand slam off of Edinson Vólquez, becoming the first shortstop to hit a grand slam in Major League Baseball postseason history.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford batted .304 (7-for-23) with 4 RBIs in the 2014 World Series, en route to his second championship with the Giants.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In Game 7, Crawford drove in the second run for the Giants with a sacrifice fly and, along with second baseman Joe Panik, turned a critical double-play in the third inning.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On January 27, 2015, the Giants and Crawford avoided arbitration by agreeing to a one-year, $3.175 million deal.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On May 16, Crawford hit his third career grand slam (fourth including the postseason) and drove in a career-high six runs against Mike Leake of the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In May, Crawford led the team in RBIs, and on July 1, Crawford set a new career-high with his 11th home run of the season.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On July 6, Crawford was voted by his fellow Major League players as a reserve for the 2015 MLB All-Star Game.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On August 14 at AT&T Park, in an 8–5 win over the Washington Nationals, Crawford hit his 100th career double.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On September 24 at Petco Park, Crawford hit his twentieth home run of the season off of Ian Kennedy, making him the fourth Giants shortstop in franchise history to reach the milestone, after Rich Aurilia, Alvin Dark, and Travis Jackson.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford set career highs in several offensive categories, batting .256 with 21 home runs, 84 RBIs, 33 doubles, and 130 hits.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford was the first Giants' shortstop to lead the team in home runs since Bill Dahlen in 1905.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He won his first Rawlings Gold Glove Award and Silver Slugger Award, the first Giant to win both awards in the same year since Barry Bonds in 1997.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] After the 2015 season, Crawford and the Giants agreed to a six-year, $75 million contract through the 2021 season.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] The deal covered Crawford's final two years of salary arbitration and first four years of free agency.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] The contract includes a no-trade clause, meaning that Crawford has to give consent if he were to be traded.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] April 8, 2016, Crawford hit a tenth inning, walk-off home run off Joe Blanton of the Los Angeles Dodgers in a game in which the Giants had been no-hit through 71⁄3 innings and recorded only two hits.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On August 8 at Marlins Park, in an 8–7 win over the Miami Marlins that went into extra-innings, Crawford hit a career-high in base hits and singles with seven and five respectively.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] His seven hits tied the NL record for most total hits in a single game, and was the first time this feat had been done since Rennie Stennett in 1975.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] The seven hits were also a Giants all-time franchise record.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Two days later, Crawford met with Stennett at Marlins Park.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] For the 2016 season, Crawford increased his batting average to a career-best .275 in 155 games played.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Along with teammate Javier López, Crawford won the Willie Mac Award, which honors the Giants' most inspirational player.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He was awarded his second consecutive Gold Glove Award after the season.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On April 29, 2017, Crawford was placed on the 10-day disabled list due to a right groin strain.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 2017, he batted .253/.305/.403 with 14 home runs and 77 RBI, and after the season he was awarded his third consecutive Gold Glove Award.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He was the first shortstop to win three straight since Jimmy Rollins (2007–09), and the first Giant since J.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On June 27, 2018, Crawford hit a walk-off home run against the Colorado Rockies to win the game 1–0 for the Giants.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford became the first Giants player since Steve Decker in April 1991 to hit a walk-off solo homer to win a 1–0 game.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Batting .300 with ten home runs and 39 RBIs, Crawford was named the starting shortstop for the 2018 MLB All-Star Game.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford hit .193 in the second half, battling injuries throughout the second half.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] A left-handed hitter, Crawford had a higher batting average against left-hand pitching than right-hand pitching at .274.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] His average against right-hand pitching was .243.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He had the slowest baserunning sprint speed of all major league shortstops, at 25.9 feet/second.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 2018, Crawford was the Giants team winner of the Heart & Hustle Award.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford lost out on his fourth straight gold glove to Arizona Diamondbacks shortstop Nick Ahmed.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Against the Rockies on July 15, 2019, he had five hits in six at bats including two home runs and a career-high eight runs batted in during the Giants' 19-2 victory.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] The eight RBIs tied the San Francisco team record held by Willie Mays and Orlando Cepeda.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford became the first shortstop in history to record five hits and eight RBIs in one game, and the first Giant to have at least two home runs and eight RBIs in a game since Willie Mays did it in 1961.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 2020 he batted .256/.326/.465 (the highest slugging percentage of his career) with eight home runs and 23 RBIs.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He had the slowest sprint speed of all major league shortstops, at 25.7 feet per second.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On June 8, 2021, Crawford started in what was his 1,326th game playing shortstop for the Giants, passing Travis Jackson for the most games played at the position in franchise history.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On August 13, Crawford agreed to a 2-year extension worth $32 million through 2023.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In the 2021 regular season, Crawford batted .298(9th in the NL)/.373(10th)/.522 with 79 runs, 24 home runs, 11 stolen bases, and 90 RBIs (all career highs).
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On defense, he had a .983 fielding percentage (third in the NL), and a 3.76 range factor/game (3rd).
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] At the end of the season, he was third of all active players in games played at shortstop, at 1,409.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In Game 3 of the 2021 NLDS, Crawford made a leaping catch to preserve a crucial 1–0 lead for the Giants, which held to give the Giants a 2–1 series lead.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He won the 2021 National League Gold Glove Award at shortstop.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] With four Gold Glove Awards he became tied with former first baseman J.T.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He was named a 2021 Silver Slugger Award finalist.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He placed fourth in National League MVP voting.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 2022 with the Giants he batted .231/.308/.344 in 407 at bats, with nine home runs and 52 RBIs, as on defense he led the NL in range factor per game at shortstop (3.88).
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He was second of all active players in career games at shortstop (1,525).
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Following the offseason departure of fellow infielder Brandon Belt, Crawford became the longest tenured member of the Giants.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He made his first major-league appearance as a pitcher with a scoreless ninth inning of relief in a 13–3 victory over the Chicago Cubs on June 11.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 2021, Crawford had mentioned his desire to eventually pitch in a big league game, although at the time manager Gabe Kapler declined to allow it, citing Crawford’s extreme value at shortstop.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] During the appearance, Crawford’s fastball reached 89.7 mph, a speed he matched in a bullpen session earlier in the season.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On July 7, he hit a two-run home run off Austin Gomber of the Colorado Rockies, moving him into 6th place on the Giants’ San Francisco-era RBI leaderboard.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford’s 2023 season included multiple trips to the 10-day injured list.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] His season finished with him setting career lows in batting average and on-base percentage, with a slash line of 0.194/0.273/0.314.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Nearing the end of the season, speculation began to grow about Crawford’s future, not just within the organization but with regards to a potential retirement as well.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In the latter half of a season in which he set offensive career lows, Crawford remained mute about his future within the sport.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On October 1, 2023, Crawford played in what many speculated could be his final game for the Giants, a 5-2 loss against the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Prior to the game, Crawford’s four children threw the ceremonial first pitches.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Throughout the game, Crawford received standing ovations from fans, and was removed from the game by manager Kai Correa in the 9th inning, allowing him to walk off the field to one final standing ovation from the Giants fans.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] After the season drew to a close, Crawford expressed his desire to remain with the Giants in any capacity, including significantly reduced playing time.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In response to the Cardinals offering Crawford a 1-year $2 million dollar contract, his agent Joel Wolfe reached out to the Giants to explore the possibility of Crawford returning to the team.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] However, President of Baseball Operations Farhan Zaidi declined to guarantee him a roster spot, citing the difficulty in maintaining a club legend as a backup, instead inviting him to training camp as a non-roster invitee.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford referred to this as the “nail in the coffin” that led him to pursue other opportunities in the league.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford finished his Giants career with the 7th most games played, 16th most hits, 8th most doubles, 17th most home runs and 12th most RBI in team history.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On February 27, 2024, Crawford signed a one-year, $2 million contract with the St.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Louis, he slashed .169/.263/.282 with one home run and four RBI.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford was released by the Cardinals on August 20.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On November 27, 2024, Crawford announced his retirement from professional baseball.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford represented Team USA at the 2017 World Baseball Classic.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] He appeared in eight games during the tournament, posting a .385 batting average and a 1.006 OPS.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Team USA would defeat Puerto Rico in the championship game, securing their first-ever World Baseball Classic title.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] On April 26, 2025 at Oracle Park, the Giants organization, which ranged from alumni, coaches, executives, and former players, honored Crawford in a pregame ceremony.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford was also surrounded by his family.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] "Brandon Crawford Celebration Day" was broadcast live on local television on NBC Sports Bay Area.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford married former UCLA gymnast Jalynne Dantzscher in Kona, Hawaii, on November 26, 2011.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford is the brother-in-law of Olympic gymnast Jamie Dantzscher.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Crawford's sister Amy is married to pitcher Gerrit Cole.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] His sister-in-law, Jennifer Pippin (the sister of Crawford's wife), died in 2017 due to an asthma attack.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] Since 2017, Crawford has hosted the Crawford Family Charity Golf Tournament, raising funds for research to cure ALS.
[src:brandon-crawford/brandon-crawford] In 2022, Crawford was named the recipient of the Lou Gehrig Memorial Award.
